vulnerabilities.analysis:
An attacker could exploit this vulnerability to execute arbitrary code. An attacker would need to cause a specially crafted string to be inserted as a log message or log message parameter. If the system has message lookup substitution enabled, this could cause arbitrary code to be loaded from an LDAP server. Message lookup substitution is enabled by default in some versions. Other protocols can be used within the message to cause a look up to a malicious server such as LDAP(S), RMI, DNS, NIS, IIOP, CORBAL, NDS, and HTTP.

 

Mandiant has observed known Chinese and Iranian threat actor groups exploiting this vulnerability in a targeted fashion. For more information see the following Mandiant resources:

  • Log4Shell Initial Exploitation and Mitigation Recommendations
  • Log4j Vulnerability Exploited by China- and Iran-Based Espionage Actors
  • Apache Log4j 2 Vulnerability (CVE-2021-44228) Poses Critical Risk to OT Environments
  • First Glance: Financially Motivated Threat Actors Likely Exploiting CVE-2021-44228; Significant Volume of Activity Anticipated        
  • Strategic Perspective: Timeline and Resources for CVE-2021-44228 'Log4Shell'               

 

On Dec. 9, 2021, GreyNoise and Bad Packets reported observing unknown actors scanning for servers vulnerable to this vulnerability. This could be an indication of threat actor interest in exploiting this vulnerability.

 

On Dec. 10, 2021, multiple researchers and organizations claimed observation of exploitation attempts in honeypot environments. (1, 2) Mandiant observed ongoing opportunistic attempts to exploit this vulnerability.

 

On Dec. 11, 2021, 360 Netlab reported that at least two Linux botnets have adopted this vulnerability as a part of their functionality. It is believed the payloads being dropped by those botnets are coin miners but that could change. (3) Additionally, Mandiant has observed targeted exploitation attempts by various threat actors suggesting that the nature of the exploitation of this vulnerability is evolving.

 

On Dec. 12, 2021, Cisco Talos reported observing exploitation activity starting as early as Dec. 2, 2021. Additionally, Cloudflare reported seeing exploitation activity as early as Dec. 1, 2021. Mandiant has yet to confirm these reports; however, exploitation activity prior to the release of public PoC or exploit code is likely to be more targeted in nature and could be evidence of more sophisticated threat actor involvement.

 

As of Dec. 14, 2021, at least one ransomware group has used this vulnerability in order to deploy ransomware on target environments.

 

On Dec. 16, 2021, an exploit for this vulnerability was incorporated in the SAINT pentesting software.

 

On Dec. 16, 2021, Blumira Detection and Response disclosed and demonstrated a new attack method utilizing WebSockets to enable local exploitation. For more information, please see the full article.

 

On Dec. 19, 2021, exploitation of this vulnerability targeting webservers was observed delivering DRIDEX and/or METERPRETER payloads.

 

On Jan. 11, 2022, Check Point Research published a blog detailing suspected Iranian actors' use of a modular PowerShell toolkit that exploits this vulnerability. The toolkit contains several modules that allows an actor to manually perform different actions on a victim's system. For more information, please see the full blog. 

 

On Jan. 14, 2022, Rapid7 and other security firms reported exploitation targeting vulnerable VMware Horizon servers. This exploitation typically uses a PowerShell payload to drop a cryptominer. In some instances this exploitation has utilized Cobalt Strike to enable a backdoor on the compromised system.

 

On Sept. 14, 2022, CISA reported, via a joint Cybersecurity Advisory, that this vulnerability has been used by a Iranian government-sponsored APT actors to gain initial access for ransom operations.

 

On Nov. 21, 2022, SANS reported exploitation involving actors gaining reverse shells through use of this vulnerability with Nashorn, a JavaScript engine.

 

Mandiant has continued to observe interest from threat actors throughout December 2021, including but not limited to discussion on Russian-language hacking forums.

Mandiant Threat Intelligence considers this a Critical-risk vulnerability because of the possibility of remote code execution without the need for user interaction or user permissions. The risk of this vulnerability is heightened by the widespread usage of the vulnerable software and it's embedded nature in other pieces of software.


CISA added this vulnerability to its Known Exploited Vulnerabilities Catalog on December 10, 2021, with a required remediation date of December 24, 2021.

associated_actors.description: APT41 is a Chinese state-sponsored espionage group that also conducts financially motivated activity for personal gain. The group has been active since at least 2012 and has conducted espionage operations against healthcare, high-tech, and telecommunications organizations. APT41 also carried out operations against the video game industry for financially motivated intrusions as well as to steal source code and digital certificates. The group executed multiple supply chain compromises, gaining access to software companies to inject malicious code into legitimate files before distributing updates.
associated_actors.name: APT41

associated_actors.description: UNC2448 is a cluster of threat activity we assess with high confidence conducts cyber espionage operations on behalf of the Iranian government. First observed in October 2020, UNC2448 has targeted private sector entities in Saudi Arabia and conducted widespread scanning against targets in Kuwait and Israel with the open-source fast reverse proxy tool FRP. Based on publicly available information and malware repository data, we assess with low confidence the actor has access to ransomware tools.
associated_actors.name: UNC2448

associated_actors.description: UNC3005 is a financially motivated threat cluster that has exploited CVE-2021-26084, a remote code execution vulnerability in Atlassian's Confluence, to deploy cryptocurrency miners. Following exploitation, UNC3005 has used cURL and wget to download the XMRIG cryptocurrency miner and shell scripts used to install and execute XMRIG. UNC3005 targeting appears to be opportunistic and bound by the distribution of systems vulnerable to recently disclosed vulnerabilities.
associated_actors.name: UNC3005

associated_actors.description: UNC3007 is a financially motivated threat cluster that has exploited multiple vulnerabilities in internet-facing systems to deploy the XMRIG coinminer and/or the JUNGLEJAM and ELFGATE denial-of-service utilities. UNC3007's targeting is suspected to be opportunistic, and their campaigns incorporate public exploit code very quickly, having actively exploited CVE-2021-44228, targeting Apache Log4j, and CVE-2021-26084, impacting Confluence, within one or two days of public vulnerability disclosure.
associated_actors.name: UNC3007

associated_actors.description: UNC3500 is a suspected Chinese actor that has leveraged CVE-2021-44228 to target entities in the education and telecommunications sectors. associated_actors.description:
UNC961 is a financially motivated group that Mandiant has tracked since January 2018, with confirmed activity dating back to November 2016. UNC961 has targeted a wide range of industries based in North America; however, UNC961 has also been observed targeting organizations in Northern Europe and Western Asia. The diverse victimology is primarily due to UNC961s opportunistic capitalization on large-scale, highly impactful vulnerabilities in publicly accessible applications to gain initial access. The group uses both custom and publicly available malware in their operations. UNC961 uses multiple custom tunnelers including GOPASSAGE, HOLEPUNCH, and TURNSIGN. The group also uses custom backdoors including GEODEZINE, MUTEPUT, MONEYRUN, BACKSLAP, CHILLSHELL, DARKDOOR, HOLEDOOR, and RUBYDOOR. 

UNC961 has provided access to at least two distinct follow-on actors, leading to data theft and the deployments of MAZE, EGREGOR, and RAGNARLOCKER ransomware. UNC961 has also exfiltrated PII, network reconnaissance, and business specific data from victims, although it is unclear what UNC961 does with the information. UNC961 has overlaps with Prophet Spider, a group CrowdStrike publicly reported on. UNC961 has been observed using language settings including Russian, and Traditional Chinese (Taiwan), but Mandiant has not yet determined a suspected location for this group.
associated_actors.name: UNC961

associated_actors.description: APT19 (Codoso) is a Chinese cyber espionage group that Mandiant Threat Intelligencehas tracked since at least 2010 when the group targeted the website of the Nobel Peace Prize. They are relatively sophisticated in comparison with other Chinese operators and on numerous occasions have been linked to zero-day exploits used in wateringhole intrusions as well as direct spear-phishing activity. APT19 (Codoso) has targeted a broad range of victims in the public and private sectors as well as civil society.
associated_actors.name: APT19

associated_actors.description: UNC3569 is a suspected China-nexus cyber actor of unknown motivation. UNC3569 has used SIDESTEP, OXEYE and BEACON malware and has leveraged public vulnerabilities including CVE-2021-44228 Log4j. UNC3569 reportedly has deployed a variety of ransomware payloads in affected environments, including NIGHTSKY ransomware, and ostensibly has historical infrastructure links to SOGU, a backdoor historically used to enable Chinese espionage operations.
associated_actors.name: UNC3569

vulnerabilities.description:
The Apache Software Foundation has provided the following description:

Apache Log4j2 <=2.14.1 JNDI features used in configuration, log messages, and parameters do not protect against attacker controlled LDAP and other JNDI related endpoints. An attacker who can control log messages or log message parameters can execute arbitrary code loaded from LDAP servers when message lookup substitution is enabled. From log4j 2.15.0, this behavior has been disabled by default.
